Eluxoroma: (n.) - the devotion to positive spiritual growth in the midst of underlying chaos or darkness. Eluxoroma is not merely an abstract concept; it is the gentle whisper of the universe, urging us to seek the light even when our eyes are heavy with tears. It is the hand that reaches into the abyss, not to pull us away from it but to guide us through it. For it is in traversing the shadows that we learn to truly appreciate the brilliance of the light. The journey of Eluxoroma is not about escaping the darkness, but about understanding that within every shadow lies the seed of light. It is about nurturing that seed with devotion, until it blossoms into a radiant testament to our unyielding spirit — a beacon of hope in a world that is forever oscillating between light and dark. You sent an attachment.
Ecclesiastes 2:26 and Proverbs 13:22 explain this so clearly. Ecclesiastes 2:26 says, “To the person who pleases Him, God gives wisdom, knowledge, and happiness, but to the sinner He gives the task of gathering and storing up wealth to hand it over to the one who pleases God.” Proverbs 13:22 confirms this: “A good person leaves an inheritance for their children’s children, but a sinner’s wealth is stored up for the righteous.” Here’s what’s amazing: God allows sinners to accumulate wealth, NOT to BLESS them, but to fulfill HIS PLAN. That wealth ultimately serves His people..those who live to please Him. Whether it’s through unexpected opportunities, resources, or even directly inheriting what they’ve stored up, God is using their work to provide for His own. It’s a powerful reminder to me that while the wicked may seem to thrive NOW, their wealth is temporary and doesn’t truly belong to them. God’s justice ensures that what they’ve gathered will be used for the good of His people, like us, who seek to honor Him. It’s His way of providing for us in ways we might not even see coming. So, there’s no need to envy their success...we just need to stay faithful and trust in God’s perfect timing and plan.

You sent an attachment.
The Book of Enoch is a non-canonical book that discusses Enoch’s experiences with angels, divine secrets, and the fate of the human soul. The book is apocalyptic in nature, using vivid imagery to predict the final judgment of evil. Topics covered in the Book of Enoch Fallen angels The book describes the experiences of Enoch with fallen angels who took wives, created the Nephilim, and taught advanced technology to humans. The fate of the human soul The book discusses the fate of the human soul after death. The origin of the Nephilim The book explains the origin of the Nephilim and the identity of the “sons of God” mentioned in Genesis 6:2 and 4. Enoch’s ascension into heaven The book describes Enoch’s ascension into heaven and his transformation into the angel Metatron.

28 About that time the Philistines mustered their armies for another war with Israel. King Achish told David, “You and your men will be expected to join me in battle.”

2 “Very well!” David agreed. “Now you will see for yourself what we can do.”

Then Achish told David, “I will make you my personal bodyguard for life.”

3 Meanwhile, Samuel had died, and all Israel had mourned for him. He was buried in Ramah, his hometown. And Saul had banned from the land of Israel all mediums and those who consult the spirits of the dead.

4 The Philistines set up their camp at Shunem, and Saul gathered all the army of Israel and camped at Gilboa. 5 When Saul saw the vast Philistine army, he became frantic with fear. 6 He asked the Lord what he should do, but the Lord refused to answer him, either by dreams or by sacred lots[a] or by the prophets. 7 Saul then said to his advisers, “Find a woman who is a medium, so I can go and ask her what to do.”

His advisers replied, “There is a medium at Endor.”

8 So Saul disguised himself by wearing ordinary clothing instead of his royal robes. Then he went to the woman’s home at night, accompanied by two of his men.

“I have to talk to a man who has died,” he said. “Will you call up his spirit for me?”

9 “Are you trying to get me killed?” the woman demanded. “You know that Saul has outlawed all the mediums and all who consult the spirits of the dead. Why are you setting a trap for me?”

10 But Saul took an oath in the name of the Lord and promised, “As surely as the Lord lives, nothing bad will happen to you for doing this.”

11 Finally, the woman said, “Well, whose spirit do you want me to call up?”

“Call up Samuel,” Saul replied.

12 When the woman saw Samuel, she screamed, “You’ve deceived me! You are Saul!”

13 “Don’t be afraid!” the king told her. “What do you see?”

“I see a god[b] coming up out of the earth,” she said.

14 “What does he look like?” Saul asked.

“He is an old man wrapped in a robe,” she replied. Saul realized it was Samuel, and he fell to the ground before him.

15 “Why have you disturbed me by calling me back?” Samuel asked Saul.

“Because I am in deep trouble,” Saul replied. “The Philistines are at war with me, and God has left me and won’t reply by prophets or dreams. So I have called for you to tell me what to do.”

16 But Samuel replied, “Why ask me, since the Lord has left you and has become your enemy? 17 The Lord has done just as he said he would. He has torn the kingdom from you and given it to your rival, David. 18 The Lord has done this to you today because you refused to carry out his fierce anger against the Amalekites. 19 What’s more, the Lord will hand you and the army of Israel over to the Philistines tomorrow, and you and your sons will be here with me. The Lord will bring down the entire army of Israel in defeat.”

20 Saul fell full length on the ground, paralyzed with fright because of Samuel’s words. He was also faint with hunger, for he had eaten nothing all day and all night.

21 When the woman saw how distraught he was, she said, “Sir, I obeyed your command at the risk of my life. 22 Now do what I say, and let me give you a little something to eat so you can regain your strength for the trip back.”

23 But Saul refused to eat anything. Then his advisers joined the woman in urging him to eat, so he finally yielded and got up from the ground and sat on the couch.

24 The woman had been fattening a calf, so she hurried out and killed it. She took some flour, kneaded it into dough and baked unleavened bread. 25 She brought the meal to Saul and his advisers, and they ate it. Then they went out into the night.

3-5 “When a woman makes a vow to God and binds herself by a pledge as a young girl still living in her father’s house, and her father hears of her vow or pledge but says nothing to her, then she has to make good on all her vows and pledges. But if her father holds her back when he hears of what she has done, none of her vows and pledges are valid. God will release her since her father held her back.

6-8 “If she marries after she makes a vow or has made some rash promise or pledge, and her husband hears of it but says nothing to her, then she has to make good on whatever she vowed or pledged. But if her husband intervenes when he hears of it, he cancels the vow or rash promise that binds her. And God will release her.

9 “Any vow or pledge taken by a widow or divorced woman is binding on her.

10-15 “When a woman who is living with her husband makes a vow or takes a pledge under oath and her husband hears about it but says nothing and doesn’t say she can’t do it, then all her vows and pledges are valid. But if her husband cancels them when he hears about them, then none of the vows and pledges that she made are binding. Her husband has canceled them and God will release her. Any vow and pledge that she makes that may be to her detriment can be either affirmed or annulled by her husband. But if her husband is silent and doesn’t speak up day after day, he confirms her vows and pledges—she has to make good on them. By saying nothing to her when he hears of them, he binds her to them. If, however, he cancels them sometime after he hears of them, he takes her guilt on himself.”

✨ ashanti.k ✨
How could I deal with this??? Cuz it happens way too often than I’d like…
Feb 16, 2025 10:22 am
✨ ashanti.k ✨
You sent an attachment.
Sometimes, stress feels like the tipping point for all the feelings you’ve been holding in. You tell yourself, “I’ll deal with this later,” but later never comes—until the weight becomes too much. And then, like an overflowing bottle, everything spills out: tears for your family, past mistakes, things you can’t fix, worries about if you’re doing enough, and the struggles of life itself. If this is where you are right now, I want you to know this: it’s okay to feel overwhelmed. Your tears are not a sign of weakness—they’re a release. They’re your body and mind saying, “It’s time to let this out.” Bottling up feelings often comes from a place of survival. Maybe you’ve had to be strong for others, or you felt like there wasn’t space for your emotions. But holding it all in doesn’t make the feelings go away; it only delays them. Here’s a gentle reminder: you don’t have to carry everything alone. Start by giving yourself permission to feel what’s coming up, piece by piece. Write it down, talk to someone you trust, or take a deep breath and sit with one emotion at a time. Healing happens when we allow ourselves to acknowledge the heaviness instead of running from it. You’re not alone in this. You’re doing the best you can, and that’s enough. Take it one moment at a time. You’re worth the care and compassion you so freely give to others. 💛

You sent an attachment.
"God doesn't give the people you want, but the people you need" reflects the idea that life, or a higher power, often places people in our paths for reasons we may not immediately understand. The individuals we desire to be around may not always lead us toward growth, healing, or self-realization. Instead, we often encounter people who challenge us, support us in ways we didn't anticipate, or teach us important lessons, shaping who we are and who we are meant to become. These relationships might not always be easy or comfortable, but they are necessary. Some people push us out of our comfort zones, inspire us to be better versions of ourselves, or open our eyes to perspectives we hadn't considered. Others may bring us through periods of hardship, teaching us resilience, patience, or humility. In essence, this idea encourages trust in life's journey, accepting that even difficult or unexpected relationships are part of a greater plan for our personal and spiritual growth. The people we need help us evolve, even if we don't recognize their significance right away. . . . . . #god #godisgood #godsplan #trustyourself #trusttheprocess #godalmighty #motivation #inspire #motivationalquotes #inspirational #mindset #inspiringquotes #motivator #motivationreels #inspiration #motivationalquotesoftheday #lifequotes #lifecore #lifelessons #advice #plan

✨ ashanti.k ✨
The Luo and Igbo people are two groups from Africa. They have different histories but some things about them are the same!

Where They Came From:

Luo: A long time ago, the Luo people lived in South Sudan. They moved to Kenya, Uganda, and Tanzania to find good land and water.

Igbo: The Igbo people have lived in Nigeria for a very long time. They mostly stayed in one area and moved around to farm and trade.

How They Are Alike:

Leaders: Both groups did not have one big boss. They worked together in small groups to make decisions.

Farming: The Luo people caught fish and took care of cows. The Igbo people mostly grew yams.

Names: Some Luo and Igbo names sound alike, but no one knows for sure if they are related. For example, the Luo name "Okongo" is similar to the Igbo name "Okonkwo." Another example is "Akomo," which appears in both languages and means "born during a harvest."

Hard Times They Faced:

Igbo: After a big war in Nigeria, many Igbo people were treated unfairly. The war, called the Biafran War (1967–1970), started when the Igbo tried to form their own country. Many people suffered, but over time, the Igbo became very successful in business and education.

Luo: In Kenya, Luo people were sometimes left out of important decisions. They were also involved in political struggles, especially against the Kikuyu group. Some Luo leaders, like Oginga Odinga and Raila Odinga, have worked hard to fight for fairness in Kenya.

Even though they have some things in common, no one knows for sure if they are from the same ancestors. Their similarities might just be part of how different African cultures grew over time.

✨ ashanti.k ✨
You sent an attachment.
When you’ve got a dad who’s absent and a mom who’s overly present, it sets up a really tough dynamic for a kid to grow up in. Dad’s absence sends the message, “You’re not valuable enough for me to stick around” while mom’s over-involvement puts you on a pedestal, making you feel like “you’re her whole world.” And so on the outside, you might come across as confident or even arrogant, but on the inside, you’re likely struggling with insecurity and imposter syndrome. The thing is, these are two separate wounds: one from a mother who used her child to heal her own pain, and the other from a father who left to deal with his own pain. It’s not just your “ego” or “insecurity”—it’s two different wounds that need to be unpacked and understood on their own. #mentalhealth #trauma #mentalhealthawareness #parenthood #parents #healing #emotionalwounds #healingjourney
